In general, the canonical structure of a test is 1) setting clear input, 2) calling the role 3) verify actual output. The tests act as a strict border guard. The more pedantic they are, the more effective they are, and yes the more time consuming they are to maintain them pedantic. In this case you're using a single point to define both input and output. It's fine in this case as it's not influencing the result of the tests, And the definition is close enough to the output to make a quick check. But in many other cases, it may happen that you set the input wrong, and the test won't stop a bad behaviour of the code, because both code and tests act and agree on the same wrong value.
To me it's a bit disorienting that the input are set at the bottom, but that is a matter of habit.

In general, the test name should be very specific and descriptive. Unofficial naming scheme is usually "${set_input}_${behaviour}_${expected_output}" So in this case, it would be something like test generate role with standard input, no debug, output-file only.

I didn't look close enough, but it seems to me, that this single test would be enough. Since the code doesn't have if/then branches, in this single test, you're covering the whole code in the role. Testing with different input in this case is less relevant, since all the input is treated in the same way in the whole code. A different test is necessary if different input leads to different code coverage. Writing correctly test names may help you detect how many test you really need. ovsdbapp/backend/ovs_idl/command.py.message:
Hi Terry:

Excuse if this comment has no sense. If self.result if going to be a row or a rowview, why don't retrieve first the UUID from this object and then try to "get_insert_uuid"?

Something like:
_uuid = getattr(self.result, 'uuid', self.result)
real_uuid = txn.get_insert_uuid(_uuid) or _uuid

Because get_insert_uuid() in python-ovs returns the permanent uuid assigned by ovsdb-server based on the temporary uuid that was returned by txn.insert(). If that lookup fails, it returns None. We don't want to possibly try to return .rows[None], we want to return either a) The row from memory based on the new permanent UUID or b) a RowView based on the whatever self.result is set to because the Command looked up a row and returned it due to may_exist or something instead of creating a new row.

With that said, taking the Row/RowView, grabbing the uuid, then looking up the in-memory version of the Row by that uuid just to get back that same Row and convert it to a RowView is a little silly. An alternative, which may be better, is doing something like:

 real_uuid = txn.get_insert_uuid(self.result)
 if real_uuid:
     row = self.api.tables[self.table_name].rows[real_uuid]
 elif isinstance(self.result, ovs.db.idl.Row):
     row = self.result
 elif isinstance(self.result, rowview.RowView):
     return
 self.result = rowview.RowView(row)

As an aside...The only way I can think of that we'd end up in post_commit() with a non-uuid (from QoSAddCommand anyway) is either a) may_exist=True and RowView() is set as the result AND we have multiple commands in the transaction--because if QoSAddCommand was the only command, no change would be made, so txn status would be UNCHANGED, and post_commit is only run for SUCCESS or b) the QoSAddCommand object is run twice, and the previous result is already stored on the command, and somehow we fall through before setting a new result (seems impossible).

So I'm still really confused how a RowView is our key since we aren't passing may_exist=True. I thought maybe the arguments ended up shifted and may_exist might be one of the other arguments and evaluate to True...but it doesn't look like that is possible. It's still a mystery.

without the 3rd branch, wouldn't I possibly try to do a rowview.RowView(row) where row is already a RowView? I could move it before the real_uuid evaluation since we know if result isn't a UUID, get_insert_uuid will return None.

I'm still scratching the surface of this project so I can't reply to this hehehe.

BTW, the code above (in your comment) looks more explicit (and better for someone like me still learning on this code). I think you don't need the third "if" branch.

That sounds like a brittle design. Thus I would recommand to keep the existing matcher and investigate other ways to make the report more useful. For example, maybe we could skip the lines already reported in unrelated job build?

I guess what is annoying is that zuul is reporting known issues or issues that are unrelated to a change. In that situation, we could look for those errors in other job build, and if we find that a warning is always emited then it should be skipped. For example the logreduce implement this strategy by looking for build result from the periodic > gate > check pipeline that match the branch > project > tenant: https://softwarefactory-project.io/cgit/logreduce/tree/logreduce/worker.py#n124

nova/api/openstack/wsgi.py.message:
This is a big move, our first PATCH that I know of.

I apologize if this was discussed at length before, but why is this not a PUT operation?

SPEC was originally implemented using the PUT API [1], but the original PUT API was changed a lot. In addition, it is restricted by the Policy. The PUT API is for the administrative role but this will be allowed admin_or_owner role. From the IRC meeting discussed [2] and finally adopted Sean's alternative suggestion [3], and adopted PATCH to update the attached volume. If you want to get more details of this that you can review the latest merged spec [4]

[1]https://review.opendev.org/#/c/580336/32/specs/ussuri/approved/destroy-instance-with-datavolume.rst

[2]http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/nova/2020/nova.2020-02-20-14.00.log.html#l-82

[3]https://review.opendev.org/#/c/580336/32/specs/ussuri/approved/destroy-instance-with-datavolume.rst@51

[4]https://review.opendev.org/#/c/580336/35

Yeah. This was really back and forth discussed in the spec. Unfortunately the current PUT /servers/{server_id}/os-volume_attachments/{volume_id} [1] is used for the admin-only, swap volume operation. That is a fairly obscure and special API now where we cannot easily add a user facing update possibility on the attachment paramters. Adding a PATCH method would separate the swap volume from updating fields on volume attachments nicely.

[1]https://docs.openstack.org/api-ref/compute/#update-a-volume-attachment

I tried removing a bit of the redundancy with this:

    def get_unhosted_gateways(self, port_physnet_dict, chassis_with_physnets,
                              all_gw_chassis):
        unhosted_gateways = set()
        for port, physnet in port_physnet_dict.items():
            lrp_name = '%s%s' % (ovn_const.LRP_PREFIX, port)
            original_state = set(self.get_gateway_chassis_binding(lrp_name))

            # Filter out chassis that lost physnet, the cms option,
            # or has been deleted.
            actual_gw_chassis = set(
                chassis for chassis in original_state
                if not utils.is_gateway_chassis_invalid(
                    chassis, all_gw_chassis, physnet, chassis_with_physnets))

            # Check if gw ports are fully scheduled.
            if len(actual_gw_chassis) >= ovn_const.MAX_GW_CHASSIS:
                continue

            # If there are no gateways with 'enable-chassis-as-gw' cms option
            # then try to schedule on all gateways with physnets connected,
            # and filter required physnet.
            available_chassis = {
                c for c in all_gw_chassis or chassis_with_physnets.keys()
                if not utils.is_gateway_chassis_invalid(
                    c, all_gw_chassis, physnet, chassis_with_physnets)}
            available_chassis.update(actual_gw_chassis)

            if not available_chassis or available_chassis == original_state:
                # There is no chassis that could host this gateway or
                # The same situation as was before. Nothing
                # to be rescheduled.
                continue
            unhosted_gateways.add(lrp_name)
        return unhosted_gateways

keystone/identity/backends/sql_model.py.message: Question: Out of curiosity why is the table UserGroupMembership is not added as a relationship to this table whereas table expiring_user_group_memberships is?

What this does, is it adds an attribute called `user` to ExpiringUserGroupMembership objects, so that we can access the  membership's user by doing `.user`. We haven't needed to do that for normal group memberships.
remind me why this needed to be a new table instead of new attributes in the UserGroupMembership table?

If we join the tables, identity_provider would have to be part of the composite primary key as well, and any part of a primary key can't be null. That would mean that a user can't have group membership from more than one idp, or actual assignment. It's not possible for a user to have multiple idps for now, but that will change if federated attributes merges in its current form.

My response at the time was that the implementation would be cleaner since idp_id and last_active would not apply to normal groups. But after doing the driver part I'm not so sure of that anymore. I can spend a few hours this evening investigating the same table approach.
nope, can't do this. the federation driver is a separate backend from the identity driver. relationships between the two backends need to be maintained via the manager, not in sql.
We already have foreign key dependencies to the federation model regardless of this. Line 341 and 348, FederatedUser model.

workbooks/deployment.yaml.message: this doesn't seem right. This option is for a user who wants to pass in a custom ansible.cfg where the options specified within will override the values from our generated ansible.cfg.
in ps5 I put the input back but made it so that if the override is null it will default to our generated ansible.cfg file.

the config specified with --override-ansible-cfg is merged with the generated config in write_default_ansible_cfg in tripleo_common/actions/ansible.py.

If there are the same keys in both, the values from the override will take precedence since it is read last with the ConfigParser object.

I may be wrong here, but in reading our tripleo-common ansible code it seems that if a user provides an ansible.cfg file it will replace our generated config, not extend it, and if this happens, its likely nothing will work.

I will say that we've added the ability to set the config via the client when playbooks are executed, so users will be able to provide a config to their liking, however, giving users the ability to control the config options when we have so many configuration settings that are hard coded for our specific systems seems like a foot gun, eventually leading to a bad user experience.
i don't see how this can be removed either until the config_download_deploy workflow is fully migrated
The key is in our generated ansible.cfg file so there's no need to provide the key here.
this won't pass CI if you don't pass a key in. I think this patch needs to wait until config_download_deploy is migrated as well.
this isn't right. i don't think this line needs to be changed at all.

sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/common/servi.message: is this allowed to be updated via api; and will there be any semantic checks required for that?

Puppet will not gracefully avoid updating configmap. I changed it now to only allow the pod security policy plugin. I also add the existing plugin by default so it doesnt show up on service parameters (looks weird if user enters 1 plugin in service parameters, runs a list command, and sees 2)

What happens if the user passes in garbage (e.g. non-alphanumeric or a plugin that doesn't exist)? Will the puppet manifest gracefully avoid updating the config map? How would the user know that an error was made?

This is allowed to be updated via api, but we cannot really put any semantic checks. The accepted string is a comma separated list of plugins. Kubernetes could add more in the future, and we do not want to maintain an internal list of valid kubernetes plugins.

/COMMIT_MSG.message:
Can you change the above to:

DRAC: Fix a failure to create virtual disk bug

Can you change the above to:

Certain RAID controllers (PERC H730P) require physical disks to be switched from non-RAID (JBOD) mode to RAID mode to be included in a virtual disk.  When this conversion happens, the available free space on the physical disk is reduced due to some space being allocated to RAID mode housekeeping.  If the user requests a virtual disk (a RAID 1 for example) with a size close to the max size of the physical disks when they are in JBOD mode, then creation of the virtual disk following conversion of the physical disks from JBOD to RAID mode will fail since there is not enough space due to the space used by RAID mode housekeeping.

This patch works around this issue by recalculating the RAID volume size after physical disk conversion has completed and the free space on the converted drives is known.  Note that this may result in a virtual disk that is slightly smaller than the requested size, but still the max size that the drives can support.

It should be '/servers/detail?config_drive=False'
like https://review.opendev.org/#/c/713089/6/novaclient/tests/unit/v2/test_servers.py@91, shouldn't it?

It seems that the filtering problem is general for every integer filter. 0 value is considered a no-filter-provided instead of filter-with-0. So this also fails

    def test_list_with_0_progress(self):
        self.run_command('list --progress 0')
        self.assert_called('GET', '/servers/detail?progress=0')

To reproduce the filtering bug for 0 I noted in in the shell.py you can add a test like:

    def test_list_with_power_state_filter_for_0_state(self):
        self.run_command('list --power-state 0')
        self.assert_called('GET', '/servers/detail?power_state=0')

The nova API is suboptimal (to say it nicely) in this regard:

"config_drive - body -string

Indicates whether or not a config drive was used for this server. The value is True or an empty string. An empty string stands for False."

So if on the CLI we define --config-drive as boolean filter then
* --config-drive false should be translated to GET /servers/detail?config_drive=
* --config-drive True should be translated to GET /servers/detail?config_drive=True

BUT I think I discovered a nova bug which, I think, prevents us to filter servers that has no config drive [1] so the first bullet point will not work.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1871409

After a discussion, see[2], it seems that the bug is not easy to fix. So I think we need to decouple the client support of 2.83 from this bug. I suggest to change the --config-drive param to a string param and let the client blindly pass the string to the Nova API. 
When [1] is fixed the we can make the client stricter too.

[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1871409/comments/2

manila/tests/api/v2/test_share_replicas..message: Since I have the need_to_update_usages flag in the share_replica_delete method, I think that there is no need to mock this anymore.
This API shouldn't be calling into the quotas code?

The share replica usages are being updated in the share_instance_delete (which is called by the share_instance_delete method). So the reserve/commit of quotas were being called, since the need_to_update_usages flag was ever being set to true. But in the most recent version of this change, I have added a need_to_update_usages parameter to the share_replica_deleted method as well, and then I'm able to make this unit test avoid the quotas reserve/commit by setting that flag to false.

Thanks. The new example would be better.

This could lead to clients having to perform a large number of requests, one for each key. What about adding another call like with Nova GET /v2.1/servers/detail?

GET /v1/<resource_type>/properties/detail would return all keys and their values.

Sure, though in that case I would prefer an API that responds in a general structure that gets "filled in" if a ?detail=1 argument is passed, e.g.:

  [
    { "property": "local_gb" },
    { "property": "memory_mb" },
    ..
  ]

With ?detail=1:

  [
    { "property": "local_gb", "values": [..] },
    { "property": "memory_mb", "values": [..] },
    ..
  ]

What do you think about that?
That should be fine as well.

I was going to say that these are hypervisor_properties rather than network_properties, but in my development environment reserving with either produces the same result. I need to check what is exactly the difference.

This has confused me as well, because from what I can tell, there is no difference: https://opendev.org/openstack/blazar/src/branch/master/blazar/plugins/oshosts/host_plugin.py#L570-L575

Yet, in at least one place, only resource_properties is used: https://opendev.org/openstack/blazar/src/branch/master/blazar/plugins/oshosts/host_plugin.py#L412-L413

My proposal going forward would be to drop the plugin-specific *_properties and just use resource_properties as a general filter/selection mechanism across all plugins.
Would it make sense to hide count for operators who want to hide details about the size of their infra?

The use case would be any commercial cloud? I could see this API being useful for their UI, yet not wanting to show this data. 

I am hesitant to define count in the API, as we cannot remove it later. 

If the rationale for providing count is to give information about the number of available resources for each user, it may be too limited anyway as they may want to know how many resources exist for a combination of properties.
Done
Let's do that and revisit count in a future spec.

I'm not sure--is that a real use case? I'd propose we default to exposing this (operators can always completely disable this API if they want). Maybe another policy can handle confidentiality of that granularity if we end up needing it later.
The point about combinations makes sense. Given that, I propose we just remove the "count" value for now.
likelihood
Done
This is an odd behavior given that we would make existing capabilities private. I would prefer if it was private by default, but configurable via blazar.conf.
Sure, we can default to private if you want. I think default=public makes more sense long term, so we will require lots of deployments overriding this, but it is a bit safer.

test-requirements.txt.message: I am wondering if this should this be 4.0.0, instead. It seems like any release up to the next major revision bump should be compatible. I am assuming semver applies here.
That makes sense. Thank you for the explanation!

This was done more to stick with a specific version and be consistent between all the other projects that we updated.
Usually there are no big changes in minor revisions, so we could move the top limit version to 4.0.0 not included.
Just considering that this library doesn't get a lot of changes, we risk to come back to it and find surprises, but that could happen with all the rest of the dependencies.
